      "question": "If $\\tan(A+B) = \\sqrt{3}$ and $\\tan(A-B) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}$, where $0^\\circ < A+B \\le 90^\\circ$ and $A > B$, find the values of $A$ and $B$.",
      "answer": "$A = 45^\\circ, B = 15^\\circ$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the values of tangent from the trigonometric table for $A+B$ and $A-B$.",
          "Set up a system of linear equations in $A$ and $B$.",
          "Solve the system using elimination method."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\tan(A+B) = \\sqrt{3} \\implies A+B = 60^\\circ \\quad (1) \\\\ \\tan(A-B) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\implies A-B = 30^\\circ \\quad (2) \\\\ (1)+(2): 2A = 90^\\circ \\implies A = 45^\\circ \\\\ (1)-(2): 2B = 30^\\circ \\implies B = 15^\\circ$"
      },
